-- WP10 (docs/spec/WASM-SEMANTICS.md §1) — the once-S0 SILENT arm of #553, NOW FIXED
-- and serving as a REGRESSION LOCK. Golden is `42` (the correct answer).
--
-- ✅ FIXED by #553 Stage B (2026-07-17). This fixture pinned the bug below and PROMOTED
-- when the fix landed: eval==native==wasm now all print 42, the `emitter:shared-eager-init`
-- ledger row was deleted, and this golden was re-blessed 0 -> 42. It now FAILS (prints 0)
-- if Stage B is reverted, so keep it and its `42` golden. Do NOT delete this fixture.
--
-- THE BUG IT LOCKS. A nullary top-level binding is an eagerly-initialized global. Both
-- backends order those with a topo sort. Pre-Stage-B its edges came from the SHARED
-- `eagerVars` (compiler/backend/emit_support.mdk) — a DIRECT free-var scan that did NOT
-- follow calls into a callee. So `cell = mkVal ()` yielded the single edge `mkVal`: a
-- FUNCTION, not a value bind, hence no edge at all. `base` was invisible, source order
-- decided, and `cell` initialized first — reading `base`'s still-zero cell (native 0,
-- exit 0, a silent lie; wasm trapped at instantiate, which killed the playground, #543).
-- Stage B's `eagerReachMap` follows the call to `mkVal` and sees the `base` edge.
--
-- Measured on the shipping engines after Stage B (2026-07-17): eval 42, native 42, wasm 42.
--
-- The peer `eager_global_call_ordered.mdk` is the CONTROL: same program, `base` moved
-- ABOVE `cell`, all three engines agree on 42 — which proves the ONLY variable here was
-- declaration order. Build-path twin: test/build_diff_fixtures/eager_call_hidden.mdk.

mkVal _ = base

cell = mkVal ()

base = 42

main = cell
